resources.string:
1. Install the APK on the host phone.
2. Connect the target device through USB OTG.
3. Put the second device into Fastboot or Recovery Sideload.
4. Put .img/.zip files into /sdcard/Download/NekoMiFlash or press “Import”.
5. Press “Scan USB”. If several devices are found, choose the required one.
6. Grant USB access. If Android does not respond within 30 seconds, reconnect OTG.

Cable and OTG:
• the host phone must support USB OTG;
• USB-C ↔ USB-C works only if the cable transfers data;
• microUSB requires an OTG adapter;
• if the device is not found, try another data cable or a powered USB hub.

Fastboot:
• “Flash .IMG” remains available for guided download → flash;
• manual terminal accepts fastboot getvar/flash/erase/format/oem/flashing/reboot and raw commands;
• fastboot flash <partition> <file.img> uses /sdcard/Download/NekoMiFlash for relative paths;
• file-based operations still check getvar, max-download-size, and sidecar .sha256/.md5.

Forum diagnostics:
• “Auto” checks USB every 3 seconds and reports new devices;
• “Debug” adds detailed USB/Fastboot lines to the log;
• “Report” creates a ZIP with log.txt, usb-info.txt, fastboot-info.txt, and app-info.txt.

Files and logs:
• “Import” copies .img/.zip/.bin/.sha256/.md5 into /sdcard/Download/NekoMiFlash;
• “Inspect” checks boot/vendor_boot/vbmeta/sparse/zip before flashing;
• “Log” shares the log as a .txt file through FileProvider;
• “Battery” opens battery optimization settings for long operations.

ADB:
• ADB Sideload remains a dedicated recovery/sideload action;
• manual terminal supports adb shell, adb exec, adb reboot, and raw ADB service;
• push/pull/sync require the separate ADB sync protocol and are not emulated yet.

Device profiles:
• folder: /sdcard/Download/NekoMiFlash/profiles;
• sample is created automatically;
• a profile warns if the selected partition is not listed in allowed_partitions.
